  "total_points": 9,
  "stimulus": "At time $t \\geq 0$, a particle moving along a curve in the $xy$-plane has position $\\bigl(x(t),\\, y(t)\\bigr)$ with velocity vector $\\mathbf{v}(t) = \\left\\langle \\cos(t^2),\\, e^{0.5t} \\right\\rangle$. At $t = 1$, the particle is at the point $(3, 5)$.",
  "stimulus_image": null,
  "documents": null,
  "parts": [
    {
      "letter": "a",
      "prompt": "Find the $x$-coordinate of the position of the particle at time $t = 2$.",
      "point_value": 3,
      "scoring_notes": null,
      "requires_drawing": false,
      "reference_image": null,
      "scoring_points": [
        {
          "point_id": "a1",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct integral expression for $x(2)$ using the Fundamental Theorem: $x(2) = x(1) + \\int_1^2 \\cos(t^2)\\,dt$",
          "official_rubric": "1 point: $x(2) = 3 + \\int_1^2 \\cos(t^2)\\,dt$",
          "sample_responses": [
            {
              "response": "$x(2) = x(1) + \\displaystyle\\int_1^2 x'(t)\\,dt = 3 + \\int_1^2 \\cos(t^2)\\,dt$",
              "earned": true,
              "commentary": "Correctly applies the Fundamental Theorem using the known $x$-position at $t=1$ and the $x$-velocity component.",
              "source": "synthesized"
            },
            {
              "response": "$x(2) = \\displaystyle\\int_0^2 \\cos(t^2)\\,dt$ (integrates from $0$ instead of $1$)",
              "earned": false,
              "commentary": "Integrates from $t=0$ but the position at $t=0$ is unknown; only the position at $t=1$ (which is $x=3$) is given.",
              "source": "synthesized"
            }
          ],
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$x(2) = 3 + \\int_1^2 \\cos(t^2)\\,dt$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "a2",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct numerical evaluation of the integral",
          "official_rubric": "1 point: $\\int_1^2\\cos(t^2)\\,dt \\approx -0.450$",
          "sample_responses": [
            {
              "response": "$\\displaystyle\\int_1^2\\cos(t^2)\\,dt \\approx -0.450$",
              "earned": true,
              "commentary": "Correct calculator evaluation of the Fresnel-type integral.",
              "source": "synthesized"
            },
            {
              "response": "$\\displaystyle\\int_1^2\\cos(t^2)\\,dt = \\sin(t^2)\\Big|_1^2 = \\sin 4 - \\sin 1 \\approx -0.244$ (wrong antiderivative)",
              "earned": false,
              "commentary": "Attempts an algebraic antiderivative: $\\int \\cos(t^2)\\,dt \\neq \\sin(t^2)/(2t)$; this integral has no elementary antiderivative and must be evaluated numerically.",
              "source": "synthesized"
            }
          ],
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$\\int_1^2 \\cos(t^2)\\,dt \\approx -0.450$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "point_id": "a3",
          "point_value": 1,
          "description": "Correct final answer: $x(2) \\approx 3 + (-0.450) \\approx 2.550$",
          "official_rubric": "1 point: $x(2) \\approx 2.550$",
          "sample_responses": [
            {
              "response": "$x(2) = 3 + (-0.450) \\approx 2.550$",
              "earned": true,
              "commentary": "Correctly adds the integral result to the initial $x$-position.",
              "source": "synthesized"
            },
            {
              "response": "$x(2) = 3 + 0.450 = 3.450$ (sign error)",
              "earned": false,
              "commentary": "Uses $+0.450$ instead of $-0.450$. The integral $\\int_1^2\\cos(t^2)\\,dt$ is negative because $\\cos(t^2) < 0$ for much of the interval.",
              "source": "synthesized"
            }
          ],
          "alternatives": [
            {
              "required_elements": [
                "$x(2) \\approx 2.550$"
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "letter": "b",
      "prompt": "For $0 < t < 1$, there is a point on the curve at which the line tangent to the curve has a slope of $2$. At what time is the particle at that point? Give a decimal approximation.",
